ChatGPT said:

This curriculum is solid as a learning roadmap — it’s well-structured, builds progressively, and touches the main pillars of observability (logs, metrics, traces, error monitoring). You won’t be “missing something major” if your intent is learning and hands-on practice.
But if you’re aiming at production-grade mastery, there are some important gaps:

✅ Strengths in your plan

  • Covers the three observability pillars (logging, metrics, tracing).

  • Phases are logically ordered: logs → aggregation → errors → metrics → tracing → integration → production scale.

  • Good mix of concepts and hands-on tasks.

  • Stacks/tools chosen (Pino, Promtail, Loki, Prometheus, Grafana, Jaeger, Sentry) are standard, widely used, and free/self-hostable.

  • Explicit inclusion of RabbitMQ monitoring (many miss this).

  • Includes runbooks and failure simulation (real learning).

⚠️ Missing or under-emphasized areas

  1. Log retention & storage scaling

    • Loki/Elastic will grow fast with real workloads. Need strategy for retention, compression, and cost management.

    • Missing: log rotation policies, storage backends (S3, GCS).

  2. Metrics completeness

    • You listed CPU, latency, error rate, queue size — good start.

    • Missing: DB metrics (Postgres/MySQL exporters), cache metrics (Redis exporter), container metrics (cAdvisor/Node Exporter).

    • In production, you need infrastructure + application + business metrics.

  3. Tracing context propagation pitfalls

    • In polyglot systems (Node.js + Python), context propagation often breaks if not carefully configured. Worth practicing how headers (e.g., traceparent) move across services and RabbitMQ.

  4. Security & compliance

    • Logs/metrics/traces may leak PII, API keys, tokens.

    • Need to practice redaction, filtering, and encryption.

    • Access control on Grafana, Loki, Jaeger is non-optional in real systems.

  5. Alert fatigue & SLOs

    • You mention alerts, but not alert design.

    • In production, you should learn about SLIs/SLOs (latency, error rate, availability targets) to avoid spammy or useless alerts.

  6. Service discovery / scaling

    • Your Docker Compose setup is great for learning, but for production, scraping Prometheus and routing logs/traces in Kubernetes requires service discovery (Prometheus Operator, Helm charts). That’s not mentioned.

  7. Correlation beyond request ID

    • Request IDs are fine for synchronous flows, but in RabbitMQ async pipelines you may need custom correlation IDs or message headers for tracing/logging consistency.

🧭 Recommendation

  • If your goal = learning path → This is perfectly fine. Start as is.

  • If your goal = real production readiness → You’ll need to expand into:

    • exporters for infra (DB, cache, OS, container)

    • log retention/cost management

    • security/redaction practices

    • proper alert design (SLIs/SLOs)

    • service discovery in Kubernetes

👉 So: Your roadmap is good enough to start. You’re not “missing” essentials for learning, but you are missing key pieces for running this in a real production cluster.

Alright, one concrete project that fits your stack (Node.js + TypeScript + Docker + RabbitMQ + Python) and naturally forces you to implement logging, monitoring, and observability is:

📦 Order Processing Microservices System

Concept

Simulate a mini e-commerce backend where multiple microservices handle different responsibilities:

  • API Gateway (Node.js + TypeScript)

    • Exposes REST endpoints (/order, /status).

    • Accepts orders from clients.

    • Publishes messages to RabbitMQ.

  • Order Service (Node.js + TypeScript)

    • Listens to “orders” queue.

    • Validates order.

    • Writes order to a database (SQLite/Postgres).

    • Emits events (e.g., “order_validated”).

  • Payment Service (Python)

    • Subscribes to “payments” queue.

    • Simulates payment processing (random success/failure).

    • Publishes events like “payment_success” or “payment_failed”.

  • Notification Service (Node.js or Python)

    • Subscribes to “notifications” queue.

    • Sends mock emails/SMS (just logs message to stdout).

Why this project works for your learning path

  • Logs: Each service logs its activity (order received, payment failed, etc.) with request IDs.

  • Errors: Payment failures, DB connection errors, invalid orders → captured via Sentry.

  • Metrics:

    • Orders created/sec (API).

    • Payment success rate (Payment service).

    • Queue size (RabbitMQ exporter).

    • Latency for order processing (end-to-end).

  • Tracing:

    • Trace flow: API → Order Service → RabbitMQ → Payment Service → Notification Service.

  • Observability Stack: Run Promtail + Loki + Prometheus + Grafana + Jaeger + Sentry alongside services in Docker Compose.

Phased Learning with this Project

  • Phase 1 (Structured logs): Add Pino/structlog, correlate logs by orderId.

  • Phase 2 (Log aggregation): Centralize all service logs into Loki/Grafana.

  • Phase 3 (Error monitoring): Crash Payment service randomly → Sentry alerts.

  • Phase 4 (Metrics):

    • Prometheus: request latency, order count, payment success rate.

    • RabbitMQ queue length.

  • Phase 5 (Tracing): Trace end-to-end order flow with OpenTelemetry.

  • Phase 6 (Integration): View logs + metrics + traces in Grafana while simulating failures.

👉 This one project can carry you through the whole roadmap without being trivial, and it’s close to real-world patterns (API → async processing → external integration).

Yes — you can absolutely mix in cloud options into this project while still following the same roadmap. It’s actually smart, because you’ll learn self-hosted OSS tools and how to offload parts of observability to cloud services (which is what most real systems do).

Here’s how you can weave cloud options into the same Order Processing Microservices project:

🌩️ Mixing Cloud into Your Observability Path

Phase 1 — Structured Logging

  • Keep it local (Pino, structlog).

  • But: send logs to a cloud log store in parallel (e.g., AWS CloudWatch, GCP Logging, or Logtail/Papertrail).
    → You’ll see difference: local JSON logs vs. cloud log ingestion.

Phase 2 — Centralized Log Aggregation

  • Option A (OSS path): Loki + Promtail + Grafana in Docker Compose.

  • Option B (Cloud):

    • Send logs to AWS CloudWatch Logs or GCP Logging.

    • View logs directly in their consoles.

  • Hybrid: keep local Loki for dev, but also push structured logs to CloudWatch/GCP for practice.

Phase 3 — Error Monitoring

  • Instead of self-hosting Bugsnag/Rollbar, just use Sentry Cloud (free tier).

  • Benefit: realistic alerting workflows (email/Slack integration).

Phase 4 — Metrics & Health Checks

  • Option A: Prometheus + Grafana (local).

  • Option B (Cloud):

    • Use Grafana Cloud (free tier) → supports Prometheus remote-write.

    • Or push metrics to AWS CloudWatch Metrics (via SDK).

  • This teaches you: difference between scraping (Prometheus pull model) vs. pushing metrics to a cloud service.

Phase 5 — Tracing

  • Option A: Jaeger/Tempo (self-host).

  • Option B: Cloud APM (e.g., Datadog APM, New Relic, Grafana Cloud Tempo).

  • Example: use OpenTelemetry SDK, but send traces to Grafana Cloud Tempo instead of local Jaeger.

Phase 6 — Unified Observability

  • Local dev stack = Loki + Prometheus + Jaeger + Grafana.

  • Cloud hybrid =

    • Logs → CloudWatch/GCP Logging

    • Metrics → Prometheus (local) and Grafana Cloud

    • Traces → Jaeger (local) and/or Grafana Cloud Tempo

    • Errors → Sentry Cloud

This dual setup will force you to understand local OSS tooling vs. managed SaaS/cloud services, and when to pick which.

Phase 7 — Scale / Production

  • Deploy same services into ECS (AWS), GKE (GCP), or AKS (Azure) with:

    • Sidecar/log driver sending logs to CloudWatch/Stackdriver.

    • Prometheus Operator or Managed Prometheus for metrics.

    • Cloud Sentry for errors.

    • Managed tracing backend (Grafana Cloud, Datadog, etc).

⚡ Best Cloud Mix for Learning (minimal free-cost burden):

  • Logs → CloudWatch Logs (AWS free tier)

  • Errors → Sentry Cloud (free tier)

  • Metrics → Prometheus locally + Grafana Cloud (free tier)

  • Tracing → OpenTelemetry SDK → Grafana Cloud Tempo (free tier)

This way, you’ll learn both sides:

  • How to self-host observability stack in Docker Compose.

  • How to integrate with cloud-native observability services.
